# **Introduction** {#introduction}

This past fall, I did a lot of experiments with my credit card sized computer’s GPIO pins. These GPIO (general purpose input-output) pins allow me to program different electrical components such as small LEDs, motors, and relay switches.

Dealing with the physical hardware of a computer is not exactly my thing. I deal with front-end things alot, meaning the user experience. However, I recently found a simple way to control these components (back-end) with a web browser (front-end).

I am going to be walking you through the basics of how I built my software for my future vending machine.

# **Making some plans** {#making-some-plans}

Since I was little, I have always liked things around entrepreneurship, marketing and other technologies that many businesses use — and a project I have always wanted to make is a vending machine. My most favorite vending machine is the Freeosk sample machine at Sam’s Club, and when making the plans for this one I wanted to make it somewhat alike.

### **THE BIGGEST FEATURE I WANTED** {#the-biggest-feature-i-wanted}

The biggest feature I wanted with this vending machine is flexibility. I wanted to be able to use this for a variety of different purposes. One of my favorite ideas is to make a halloween candy dispenser that uses voice recognition to require you to say  “trick-or-treat” before giving you candy or I could embed a game that when you get to a certain level, it gives you a prize.  
Most importantly, I wanted it to have a good user experience, that is simple, bold, aesthetically pleasing, and that sells the product.

# **The Backend of things** {#the-backend-of-things}

After doing some quick research, I found that a backend of Node.js would be the best option. Node.js, in my opinion, is one of the coolest backends out there. It uses a language that is normally used for front-end development called JavaScript. The super cool part is JavaScript is the language that web browsers use in the front end, so I didn't need to learn a new backend language to make this work\! Node.js is not the normal way of doing this. Normally you would code the entire thing using a backend language like python, but I wanted to challenge myself to do it using a different method.

# **Setting things up and preparing for coding** {#setting-things-up-and-preparing-for-coding}

Before I started working on the vending machine, I used a tutorial from W3Schools, a website that can teach you to code in nearly any language. I started out with their simple tutorial on how to blink a LED using Node.js. The first thing I needed to do was wire the LED to a GPIO pin on the Raspberry Pi.  
![][image1]![][image2]  
I am using Ubuntu OS, and Ubuntu doesn't come with Node pre-installed. I had to run a few commands to install Node. The next thing I needed to do was to install a node plugin library called onoff. Onoff is specifically for controlling the raspberry pi’s GPIO pins. 

After installing onoff, I was good to go. I downloaded the code, ran it and… ERROR\! I ran into one of the many problems I faced with this project. When working with computers, it is almost normal to run into problems like these.

| THE PROBLEM: I received an error in the console when trying to use onoff. |
| :---- |
| **THE SOLUTION:** It turned out that onoff was outdated, and was incompatible with the version of node I had installed, requiring an older version of node. I was using node for other projects on the same computer that required the newer version of node so I decided not to install an older version of node, and ditch onoff altogether. Lucky for me, I found a good alternative called array-gpio that did the same thing.  |

# **Converting to array-gpio from onoff** {#converting-to-array-gpio-from-onoff}

After installing array-gpio, I also had to make some modifications to the downloaded code for it to work correctly with array-gpio, like importing array-gpio instead of onoff.

### **CODE FOR CONVERTING “ONOFF” TO “ARRAY-GPIO”** {#code-for-converting-“onoff”-to-“array-gpio”}

Node.js uses JavaScript files (.js) for backend code. All JavaScript code will use the “.js” file extension.   
**THE CODE (BEFORE):** index.js

```javascript
var Gpio = require('onoff').Gpio; //Load onoff for interaction with the GPIO
var led = new Gpio(4, 'out'); //Define the LED on GPIO 4, set it as a output 

led.writeSync(1); //turn LED on
led.writeSync(0); //turn LED off
```

**THE CODE (AFTER):** index.js

```javascript
const r = require('array-gpio'); //Load array-gpio for interaction with the GPIO instead of onoff.
let led = r.out(7); //Define the led on GPIO pin 7 and  set it as a an output. 
//Note that array-gpio doesen't use GPIO numbers, it uses pin numbers, so GPIO 4 is the same as pin 7. See https://pinout.xyz/ for the pinout diagram.
led.on(); //turn LED on
led.off(); //turn LED off
```

I ran the code…and it worked correctly. Now I can move on to the next step. 

# **Input vs. Output** {#input-vs.-output}

When working with the GPIO pins, there are 2 different types of pin interactions: inputs and outputs. Inputs are things like buttons and sensors. Anytime the positive and negative (ground) complete a circuit, there is an input event that occurs. Outputs are electrical signals that are being sent out of the computer. For example, when I run a code that turns the LED on, then electricity is being outputted to the LED.

### **HOW I PLAN TO USE OUTPUT EVENTS**

I will have 4 motors connected to my raspberry pi. The computer will turn on the motors using output events.

### **HOW I PLAN TO USE INPUT EVENTS** {#how-i-plan-to-use-input-events}

For my vending machine, I needed a way to tell the computer that the product had been dispensed. For this, I decided to use a light beam sensor. A light beam sensor brakes the circuit when the beam is broken… so when the product falls, it breaks the light beam, sending an input event to the computer to stop the motors.

# **Basic use of inputs** {#basic-use-of-inputs}

I needed an input on my vending machine, so I hooked a button to one of the pins. I wrote a simple code that whenever you press the button, the LED turns on.

```javascript
const r = require('array-gpio'); //Import array-gpio
let sw = r.in(3); //Define the button - Hook a push button switch to pin 3 (GPIO 2) 
let led = r.out(7); //Define the LED

sw.watch((state) => { //Watch the current state of the switch
  if(state){ //If the switch is on, turn the LED on
    led.on();
  }
  else{ //Otherwise, turn the LED off (switch released)
led.off();
  }
});
```

# **Adding server functionality** {#adding-server-functionality}

Now that we have input and output functionality, we can start working on the server. Directly through node.js, you can create a web server through the preinstalled “http” module. I want to be able to send and receive data from the server as well. To do this, I will use the socket.io module and it doesn't come preinstalled with node.js, so you will need to install it manually. Socket.io uses a websocket connection to send data back and forth without a need to reload the webpage. The last module we will be using is called “fs” \- for filesystem module, that allows us to access other files. The file system module comes preinstalled with node.js as well.

For the server to work, we also have to write some basic HTML code for the frontend (user side) of our server. HTML is the format used in web browsers to display text, and create the physical elements (like buttons, input fields, etc.) on websites. We now need to use 2 files, instead of one. The new 2 files are index.js and index.html

Here is the full code for the server. I explain how each part of it works, through comments in the code.

index.js

```javascript
var http = require('http').createServer(handler); //require http server, and create server with function handler()
var fs = require('fs'); //import the file system module for accessing files
var io = require('socket.io')(http) //import the socket.io for sending/recieving data and connect it to the http server. 
const {setInput, setOutput, watchInput} = require('array-gpio'); //import array-gpio

let led = setOutput(7); 
http.listen(8080); //listen to port 8080

function handler (req, res) { //create server
  fs.readFile('index.html', function(err, data) { //get the contents of the HTML file
    if (err) {
      res.writeHead(404, {'Content-Type': 'text/html'}); //show a 404 error if the page is typed wrong in the browser
      return res.end("404 Not Found");
    }
    res.writeHead(200, {'Content-Type': 'text/html'}); //set the content type to HTML
    res.write(data); //get the code
    return res.end();
  });
}
function onoff(x) {
  if (x == "1") {
    led.on();
    console.log(`led on`);

      return false;
  }
  else if (x == "0") {
    led.off();
    console.log(`led off`);

      return false;
  }
      else 
      console.log(`Error: Value "`+x+`" not found when running function "onoff()"`)
  return false;
}


io.sockets.on('connection', function (socket) {// WebSocket Connection
  var lightvalue = 0; //static variable for current status
  /*pushButton.watch(function (err, value) { //Watch for hardware interrupts on pushButton
    if (err) { //if there is any errors, log them in the console
      console.error('There was an error', err); //output error message to console
      return;
    }
    lightvalue = value;
    socket.emit('light', lightvalue); //send button status to client
  });*/
  socket.on('light', function(data) { //get light switch status from client
    lightvalue = data;
     onoff(lightvalue);
    
    }
  );
});

process.on('SIGINT', function () { //when you press "ctrl+c" in command line
    process.exit(); //exit the program, stop the server
});
```

index.html

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<meta name="viewpoint" content="wudth=defice-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<h1>Control LED light</h1>
<!--Dropdown for selecting on/off-->
<select id="light"> 
<option value="1">ON</option> <!--When ON is selected, the value is 1-->
<option value="0">OFF</option> <!--When OFF is selected, the value is 0-->
</select>

<!--Load the socket.io client-side script from the internet-->
<script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/socket.io/4.7.2/socket.io.js"></script>
 
<!--Embed a JavaScript script in the HTML using the <script> tag-->
<script> 
var socket = io(); //load socket.io-client and connect to the host that serves the page
window.addEventListener("load", function(){ //wait for page to load
var lightbox = document.getElementById("light"); //get the dropdown input by it's id "light"

lightbox.addEventListener("input", function() { //wait until dropdown value changes
socket.emit("light", this.value); //send dropdown value to server (as 1 or 0)

}); 
});
//When the button is pushed, the server sends data to the client to change the dropdown value. (1 or 0) 
socket.on('light', function (data) { //When server sends data

document.getElementById("light").value = data; //get the dropdown by id again and update the value based on what the server sends (1 or 0).
socket.emit("light", data); //send the push button status back to the server
});
</script>
<!--End the HTML document with some closing tags-->
</body>
</html>
```

# **Final server tests** {#final-server-tests}

Before I start working on the front end, I thoroughly tested my code to make sure it works.

When this code is, it will start a web server that you can access. If you open a web browser on your raspberry pi, and type “[**http://localhost:8080**](http://localhost:8080)” (or open a browser on a different device and type the Raspberry Pi’s ip address), you should see a webpage that looks something like this:  
![][image3]  
When you toggle the dropdown to on or off the LED will go on and off. If the switch is in the “on” position, then push the button and the switch will automatically turn to the “off” position. 

Everything worked correctly, so I started working on the “fun part”...the front end user experience.

# **Adding on to the code** {#adding-on-to-the-code}

I included 7 different pins for the sensor, 4 motor pins, and a multicolor status light. Because the raspberry pi can’t power motors directly from the pins, I had to purchase a $6 relay unit on Amazon.  
I added a stylesheet to my HTML code that made everything look better.
